{
  "result": "At dawn, the city pretends it is a quiet village. Delivery trucks whisper down alleys, pigeons rehearse their arguments on ledges, and steam rises from grates like small ghosts returning from night shift jobs. I like walking before the sidewalks remember their hurry. In that hour, every storefront is a closed eyelid, every traffic light a patient metronome, every stranger briefly a fellow conspirator in the secret of being awake.\n\nThere is a bakery on Ninth that starts working when the moon is still visible. The baker, who always has flour on one eyebrow, slides trays into the oven with the concentration of a violinist. By seven, the first loaves crackle as they cool, and the whole block smells like warmth made edible. People slow down without realizing it. A nurse on her way home buys rye. A mechanic buys two rolls and eats one before reaching the corner. A kid with a backpack presses his nose to the glass and grins at the cinnamon knots.\n\nI think cities survive on places like that: humble engines of care that ask for little attention and quietly feed everyone anyway. Not just with bread, but with rhythm, with continuity, with the comforting proof that someone, somewhere, woke up early to make something good. Maybe that is why morning feels hopeful: not because problems vanish, but because ordinary hands keep answering them with patient rituals, mixing flour, sweeping floors, unlocking doors, and saying, through action alone, we can begin again today for all.",
